Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bighorn sheep pneumonia has traditionally been considered a multifactorial disease, caused by multiple pathogens. Due to their complexity, multifactorial phenomena like this usually require integrated and sustained research efforts to be unveiled. The absence of established and universal explanations for pneumonia outbreaks contributes to conflict among wildlife and livestock stakeholders over land use and management practices.

The bighorn sheep pneumonia web-of-causation may have an important environmental component. Recent die-offs of bighorn sheep in several locations suggest that the proximate cause of these events may be a shared environmental determinant. If so, culling ill animals may be useless.

However, recent evidence indicates that in the northwestern USA, there seems to be a single pathogen implicated in bighorn sheep outbreaks, _Mycoplasma ovipneumoniae_, an exotic disease agent for North America introduced by domestic ovids. In this case, culling an infected herd might be an effective way to prevent the disease being transmitted to a "healthy" population. Nonetheless, if all bighorn sheep will eventually be exposed to _M. pneumoniae_, culling would actually prevent the natural selection of a resistant population or the establishment of herd immunity. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3060886,228.]
